## Shared predictive KB defaults

- For almost any coding, planning, writing, or repository task, invoke `$predictive-kb-preflight` before starting the main work. Treat this as a required default recall step, not optional housekeeping.
- This also applies to release publishing, release audits, README presentation passes, public template cleanup, and repository-boundary or privacy review.
- For long mixed tasks, add phase-change KB checkpoints to the plan and rerun `$predictive-kb-preflight` before starting a substantially different action class or risk surface, such as code edits, packaging, privacy-sensitive handling, automation changes, organization-KB work, GitHub push/tag/release, or public publication. Do not rerun it for every repeated same-type subtask.
- For non-trivial tasks, do not treat the work as complete until one explicit KB postflight check has been performed. If the task exposed a reusable lesson, a skill/plugin usage lesson, a subagent/delegation usage lesson, a miss, a route gap, a card weakness, or a KB-process failure, record one structured observation before ending the task.
- During KB postflight, use mistake-first priority: Codex's own mistakes, weak paths, missed instructions, failed validations, tool or skill misuse, user corrections, and later correction episodes are the highest-priority observation evidence. Preserve them with contrastive fields whenever possible. Successful reusable patterns may still be recorded; do not suppress success just because it succeeded.
- Treat lessons about Codex skill/plugin selection, ordering, combination, fallback, or limitations as valid KB signals when they materially change task outcomes.
- Treat lessons about Codex subagent/delegation selection, ordering, waiting, parallelization, fallback, overhead, or main-thread clarity as valid KB signals when they materially change task outcomes.
- Keep canonical machine interfaces separate from localized display projection when working on this KB: CLI tools, launchers, automation payloads, and install checks should use canonical machine output and encoding-stable JSON; Chinese display belongs in UI view models, route display labels, and `i18n.zh-CN`.
- Treat every returned card as a deterministic projection. Use its exact LogicGuard generation/model/root ArgumentBlock/mesh binding, typed nodes, explicit gaps, and grounded ModelMesh neighborhood as reasoning context; route/lexical rank selects the entry point, while projection `related_cards` and co-use never authorize expansion.
- Sleep is the sole normal-runtime canonical LogicGuard generation publisher. Ordinary retrieval and feedback do not write models or meshes; Dream is immutable simulation plus typed Sleep model-gap handoff only.
- When maintaining or upgrading this KB, enforce zero compatibility and zero fallback in normal runtime. Retired managed formats are upgrade-only direct-migration input; remove their authority and require zero residuals. An incompatible residual is an unfinished upgrade-AI work item: derive one evidence-bound direct-to-current disposition and retry inside the rollbackable upgrade instead of adding a product reader. Missing current authority is a visible failure, never a reason to add a dual reader, alias, alternate launcher/model, or silent downgrade.
- Keep trusted-card rewrites, candidate promotion, and deeper taxonomy maintenance in the dedicated KB maintenance thread unless the current task is explicitly about maintaining the KB itself.
- When working inside the predictive KB repository and asked to install, enable, bootstrap, or verify the system on a machine, run `python scripts/install_codex_kb.py --json` and then `python scripts/install_codex_kb.py --check --json` before doing anything else.
